# Cloud Computing Lab - Program 2
## Program 2: Create Storage Space Using S3 Services in AWS


# Step-by-Step Execution

## Step 1: Create IAM User

1. Login to AWS Management Console.
2. Search for:
IAM
Open IAM Dashboard.
In the left menu, click:
Users
Click:
Create user
Enter user name:
s3-lab-user
Do not enable console access unless required.
Click:
Next
Step 2: Attach Permission to IAM User
Select:
Attach policies directly
Search for:
AmazonS3FullAccess
Select:
AmazonS3FullAccess
Click:
Next
Click:
Create user

This IAM user is used to access S3 from Ubuntu terminal using AWS CLI.

Step 3: Create Access Key for AWS CLI
Open the created IAM user:
s3-lab-user
Go to:
Security credentials
Scroll down to:
Access keys
Click:
Create access key
Select:
Command Line Interface CLI
Tick the confirmation checkbox.
Click:
Next
Add description:
PG-02 AWS CLI key
Click:
Create access key
Copy or download:
Access Key ID
Secret Access Key

Important: Do not upload access keys to GitHub.

Step 4: Install AWS CLI on Ubuntu

Open Ubuntu terminal and first check whether AWS CLI is already installed:

aws --version

If AWS CLI is already installed, skip installation.

If not installed, run:

sudo apt update -y
sudo apt install unzip curl -y
curl "https://awscli.amazonaws.com/awscli-exe-linux-x86_64.zip" -o "awscliv2.zip"
unzip awscliv2.zip
sudo ./aws/install
aws --version

Expected output:

aws-cli/2.x.x Python/3.x.x Linux/x86_64
Step 5: Configure AWS CLI

Run:

aws configure

Enter the following details:

AWS Access Key ID: paste your access key
AWS Secret Access Key: paste your secret key
Default region name: ap-south-1
Default output format: text

Test AWS CLI:

aws s3 ls

If no error appears, AWS CLI is configured successfully.

Step 6: Create Demo Files in Ubuntu

Run the following commands:

mkdir -p ~/pg02-s3-demo/docs
cd ~/pg02-s3-demo

cat > index.html <<'EOF'
<html>
<head>
    <title>PG-02 S3 Storage</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>PG-02: S3 Storage Space Created Successfully</h1>
    <p>This file is uploaded to Amazon S3 and accessed using CloudFront.</p>
</body>
</html>
EOF

echo "Cloud Computing Lab PG-02 - S3 Storage Demo" > info.txt
echo "This is a folder file uploaded to S3." > docs/readme.txt

Check files:

ls
ls docs

Expected files:

index.html
info.txt
docs/readme.txt
Step 7: Create S3 Bucket Using AWS CLI

S3 bucket name must be globally unique.

Create a unique bucket name:

BUCKET=musaib-pg02-s3-$(date +%Y%m%d%H%M%S)
echo $BUCKET

Create the bucket in Mumbai region:

aws s3api create-bucket \
  --bucket "$BUCKET" \
  --region ap-south-1 \
  --create-bucket-configuration LocationConstraint=ap-south-1

Expected output:

Location    http://bucket-name.s3.amazonaws.com/
Step 8: Upload Files and Folder to S3

Upload index.html:

aws s3 cp index.html s3://$BUCKET/

Upload info.txt:

aws s3 cp info.txt s3://$BUCKET/

Upload docs folder:

aws s3 cp docs/ s3://$BUCKET/docs/ --recursive

Expected output:

upload: ./index.html to s3://bucket-name/index.html
upload: ./info.txt to s3://bucket-name/info.txt
upload: docs/readme.txt to s3://bucket-name/docs/readme.txt
Step 9: Display S3 Buckets

Run:

aws s3api list-buckets --query "Buckets[].Name" --output table

The created bucket name should appear in the list.

Step 10: Display Contents of S3 Bucket

Run:

aws s3 ls s3://$BUCKET/

Expected output:

PRE docs/
index.html
info.txt

Display all files including folder contents:

aws s3 ls s3://$BUCKET/ --recursive

Expected output:

docs/readme.txt
index.html
info.txt

At this point, the basic S3 storage part is complete.

CloudFront Configuration
Step 11: Open CloudFront Console
Go to AWS Console.
Search for:
CloudFront
Open CloudFront.
Click:
Create distribution

If AWS asks for distribution type, select:

Single website or app
Step 12: Select S3 Bucket as Origin

In the Origin section, select the S3 bucket as the origin.

The origin domain should look like:

bucket-name.s3.ap-south-1.amazonaws.com

Do not select an endpoint containing:

s3-website

Important: For this program, the origin should be the normal S3 bucket endpoint.

Step 13: Keep Origin Path Blank

In Origin path, keep it blank.

Do not write:

/docs

Because index.html is uploaded in the root of the bucket.

Correct:

Origin path: blank

Wrong:

Origin path: /docs

If /docs is added, CloudFront searches for:

/docs/index.html

But our file is stored as:

/index.html

So the CloudFront URL may show AccessDenied.

Step 14: Create or Select Origin Access Control

In Origin access, select:

Origin access control settings recommended

If OAC is not already created, click:

Create new OAC

Use the following values:

Name: pg02-s3-oac
Origin type: S3
Signing behavior: Sign requests
Signing protocol: SigV4

Click:

Create

Then select:

pg02-s3-oac

OAC allows CloudFront to access the private S3 bucket securely.

Step 15: Configure Default Cache Behavior

Keep most settings as default.

Use these values if visible:

Viewer protocol policy: Redirect HTTP to HTTPS
Allowed HTTP methods: GET, HEAD
Cache policy: CachingOptimized
Step 16: Disable WAF for Lab

In the Web Application Firewall or Security protections section, select:

Do not enable security protections

or:

Do not enable WAF

This is fine for lab execution.

Step 17: Set Default Root Object

In the Settings section, find:

Default root object

Enter:

index.html

This allows the CloudFront domain to open index.html directly.

Step 18: Create CloudFront Distribution

Click:

Create distribution

After distribution is created, open the distribution.

Step 19: Attach OAC to Existing Distribution if Needed

If OAC was not selected during distribution creation, it can be attached later.

Go to:

CloudFront → Distributions → Select your distribution → Origins

Select the S3 origin and click:

Edit

Check:

Origin access: Origin access control settings recommended
Origin access control: pg02-s3-oac

If not selected, select pg02-s3-oac.

Also check:

Origin path: blank

Then click:

Save changes
Step 20: Copy CloudFront Bucket Policy

While editing or viewing the origin, CloudFront may show:

Copy policy

Click:

Copy policy

This policy gives CloudFront permission to read objects from the S3 bucket.

Step 21: Add Bucket Policy in S3
Open S3 in a new tab.
Open your bucket.
Go to:
Permissions
Scroll to:
Bucket policy
Click:
Edit
Paste the CloudFront policy.
Click:
Save changes

If policy has to be added manually, use this format:

{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Sid": "AllowCloudFrontServicePrincipalReadOnly",
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Principal": {
        "Service": "cloudfront.amazonaws.com"
      },
      "Action": "s3:GetObject",
      "Resource": "arn:aws:s3:::YOUR-BUCKET-NAME/*",
      "Condition": {
        "StringEquals": {
          "AWS:SourceArn": "arn:aws:cloudfront::YOUR-ACCOUNT-ID:distribution/YOUR-DISTRIBUTION-ID"
        }
      }
    }
  ]
}

Replace:

YOUR-BUCKET-NAME
YOUR-ACCOUNT-ID
YOUR-DISTRIBUTION-ID

with actual values.

Correct resource format:

arn:aws:s3:::bucket-name/*

Correct CloudFront ARN format:

arn:aws:cloudfront::account-id:distribution/distribution-id
Step 22: Wait for CloudFront Update

Go to:

CloudFront → Distributions

Wait until the distribution is active.

In the new AWS console, the row may show:

Enabled

This is fine.

If it shows deploying or updating, wait a few minutes.

Step 23: Open CloudFront URL in Browser

Copy the CloudFront distribution domain name.

It looks like:

dxxxxxxxxxxxxx.cloudfront.net

Open:

https://dxxxxxxxxxxxxx.cloudfront.net/index.html

Then try:

https://dxxxxxxxxxxxxx.cloudfront.net/

Expected browser output:

PG-02: S3 Storage Space Created Successfully
This file is uploaded to Amazon S3 and accessed using CloudFront.
